I know it’s not fatal, but at the same time I haven’t seen anybody else talking about it. Is there something I can do to resolve the warning? image 1225×242 25.4 KB

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: I believe it’s complaining because you’re creating an object and not doing anything with it.  You don’t store it in a variable for later use, and it doesn’t do anything on its own (e.g. spin off threads from the constructor).  I suspect that code is missing something, though I could only speculate as to what.

Yes, that is what I thought too, and I didn’t understand how simply instantiating a PowerDistribution would enable power distribution logging. Nonetheless, the AdvantageKit guide linked in my original post said to include it, so I did, but I do find it weird that nobody else would bring it up. This is my entire Robot.java file if that is helpful.

posts.name: amber
posts.cooked: The PowerDistribution object is patched by AdvantageKit to lazy-initialize a LoggedPowerDistribution singleton with the included parameters in its constructor.

Ah I see. So I guess my question is, is this resource leak warning okay to work with or is it going to cause issues? Should I just instantiate my own LoggedPowerDistribution , or should I assign the PowerDistribution to a variable to bypass the warning?

posts.name: Ryan Blue
posts.cooked: The “resource leak” warning in vscode is because PowerDistribution is an AutoCloseable. You can safely ignore the warning. Assigning it to a variable won’t get rid of the warning.
